9
00:00:39.060 --> 00:00:42.460
So microbiome research is the study of microbes, which include bacteria,

10
00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:46.080
fungi, and viruses that live on and within

11
00:00:46.140 --> 00:00:49.480
us, and how they impact on health and disease.

12
00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:53.800
The field has been biased, I think, substantially towards

13
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:54.400
bacteria,

14
00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:58.860
for good reasons. Bacteria make up the bulk of our

15
00:00:58.900 --> 00:01:00.000
microbiome density

16
00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:03.500
and are a little bit easier to study.

17
00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:06.140
The tools are better established for bacteria.

18
00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:10.540
But fungi and viruses have also been shown by many investigators to

19
00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:14.480
be important and I think is a rising area of

20
00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:14.940
research.

21
00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:21.300
So we each harbor on the order of 100 trillion

22
00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:25.160
microbes. They make up for about 3% of our body

23
00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:26.970
mass. Their cells

24
00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:31.460
outnumber our cells up to tenfold, and their

25
00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:34.640
genes outnumber our genes also up to tenfold.

26
00:01:36.500 --> 00:01:40.280
A lot of microbiome research has been focused on the GI tract because

27
00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:43.960
that's where the highest density of microbes are found.

28
00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:49.570
These are some of the clinical areas where microbiome scientists have

29
00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:53.350
found strong associations. So, I've grouped them here by

30
00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:57.360
topic. So the first group here is metabolic disorders like

31
00:01:57.400 --> 00:01:59.540
obesity, atherosclerosis, diabetes.

32
00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:03.620
Nutrition is intimately linked with the

33
00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.550
microbiome because the microbes are involved in digestion of

34
00:02:07.600 --> 00:02:11.480
food. A variety of inflammatory disorders are

35
00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:13.180
modulated by the microbiome.

36
00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:18.120
And then the next bubble there is neurological

37
00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:22.000
diseases. So there's a lot of active research on the

38
00:02:22.020 --> 00:02:25.900
gut-brain axis. And then finally, I think of interest

39
00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:27.320
to this audience is

40
00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:31.500
how the microbiome can relate to cancer development, so

41
00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:32.660
carcinogenesis,

42
00:02:33.940 --> 00:02:34.620
mutations,

43
00:02:35.940 --> 00:02:37.480
cancer treatment toxicities

44
00:02:38.320 --> 00:02:41.800
such as graft versus host disease, which is what I've studied, or

45
00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:45.160
checkpoint inhibitor colitis. And then finally,

46
00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:50.030
the topic of the session, cancer treatment responses, including,

47
00:02:50.340 --> 00:02:53.340
in particular, immunotherapy such as CAR T cell therapy.

48
00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:59.600
So with that, I'll introduce our first speaker, Melody Smith from Stanford

49
00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:00.720
University. Thank you.

50
00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:09.910
All right. Good morning, everyone.

51
00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:14.390
So I will be presenting on the topic of the impact of the intestinal

52
00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:18.300
microbiome on CAR T cell therapy with a discussion

53
00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:21.500
both of preclinical and clinical insights on this topic.

54
00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:25.680
The research on the intestinal microbiome in CAR T cell

55
00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:29.520
therapy is still relatively new and emerging, and so I'm going to give

56
00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:33.590
you a broad overview of both of those spaces and sort of where the

57
00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:34.560
field is at this time.

58
00:03:39.480 --> 00:03:40.480
These are my disclosures.

59
00:03:41.940 --> 00:03:45.880
So we know in the study of the microbiome that a

60
00:03:45.920 --> 00:03:48.740
variety of host intrinsic and host extrinsic

61
00:03:48.800 --> 00:03:52.180
factors can impact the efficacy of cancer

62
00:03:52.220 --> 00:03:55.549
immunotherapy. You see listed some of those

63
00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:59.040
factors. And where I want to start with the beginning of this talk is

64
00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:03.060
discuss medications and how these medications impact

65
00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:06.900
the microbiome and can lead to what we call dysbiosis or

66
00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:10.400
disruption of the microbiome. We know that of the various

67
00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:13.800
medications that can impact the intestinal microbiome,

68
00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:16.000
