92
00:05:42.530 --> 00:05:44.340
may modulate these responses.

93
00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:49.120
Before beginning to talk about antibiotics, however, I do want to highlight

94
00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:52.400
that antibiotic treatment is needed in the CAR T cell setting.

95
00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:56.420
I'm showing here retrospective data from a cohort of patients treated at

96
00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.920
Fred Hutchinson Institute in Seattle.

97
00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:02.940
They evaluated 694 patients and noted

98
00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:06.240
that of those 694 patients, there were 517

99
00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:09.980
events of mostly Grade 1 to 2 CRS, or

100
00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:13.910
cytokine release syndrome.Of those patients who had

101
00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:17.920
CRS, only 19 had events of bacteremia

102
00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:21.310
that were treated with specific antibiotics to target those

103
00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:25.180
bacteria. And so what we know, again, is that fever is the

104
00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.190
early presentation of CRS in our patients who are receiving CAR T-cell therapy, and

105
00:06:29.240 --> 00:06:33.040
a small subset of them may have true bacteremias, which require

106
00:06:33.050 --> 00:06:37.000
antibiotic treatment. So the take home message being that antibiotic

107
00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:40.860
treatment is needed in our immunocompromised patients who have fever after

108
00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.380
CAR T-cell therapy, but antibiotic stewardship will

109
00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:46.840
likely lead to improved outcomes.

110
00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:49.180
And I'll show you the data that supports that.

111
00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:53.840
So several years ago, we launched a

112
00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:57.870
collaboration between Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, when I was there as a

113
00:06:57.900 --> 00:07:01.660
postdoc in the lab of Marcel van den Brink, with investigators at the

114
00:07:01.700 --> 00:07:05.560
University of Pennsylvania, and we investigated a cohort of

115
00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:09.500
228 patients who received CD19-targeted CAR

116
00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:13.480
T-cell therapy for either non-Hodgkin's lymphoma or B-cell

117
00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:17.170
acute lymphoblastic leukemia. Here I'm showing you that

118
00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:20.540
data where we looked at exposed as any patients who

119
00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:24.480
received any antibiotic in the four weeks prior to CAR T-cell

120
00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:27.580
therapy, versus those who didn't receive antibiotics.

121
00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:31.100
And we noted that those patients who'd received antibiotics had decreased

122
00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:35.820
overall survival. A subsequent study

123
00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:39.260
has also evaluated patients who received prophylactic and

124
00:07:39.300 --> 00:07:43.200
non-prophylactic antibiotics, and they classified

125
00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.960
them as either high, more than one line of antibiotics, or low, no or

126
00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:50.960
one line. And both in the prophylactic antibiotic space

127
00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:55.160
as well as in the non-prophylactic antibiotic space, they did

128
00:07:55.220 --> 00:07:58.700
observe that patients had decreased progression-free

129
00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:02.250
survival. However, given that not all

130
00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:05.840
antibiotics are equally damaging to the gut, some of these antibiotics are

131
00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:09.330
prophylactic. For example, trimethoprim sulfamethoxazole or

132
00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:12.890
Bactrim, which is used to treat for PJP prophylaxis.

133
00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:16.300
We know that not all antibiotics are equally damaging to the gut.

134
00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.310
We focused in on antibiotics that target obligate anaerobes,

135
00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:23.860
which are gut commensals, which play an important role in gut homeostasis.

136
00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:27.740
So we looked at this classification of

137
00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:31.540
piperacillin-tazobactam, imipenem, and meropenem or

138
00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:35.520
PIM in that same period of time, four weeks prior to CAR T-cell

139
00:08:35.581 --> 00:08:39.410
therapy. And as you can see here, there was a much greater

140
00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:42.220
impact in terms of decrease in overall survival.

141
00:08:43.341 --> 00:08:47.030
I'm not showing it here today just for succinctness and the sake of

142
00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:50.480
time, but we did evaluate in a multivariate analysis

143
00:08:50.920 --> 00:08:54.700
other covariates that were potentially associated with overall

144
00:08:54.740 --> 00:08:58.700
survival to evaluate for potential confounders, asking the question whether

145
00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:02.980
these antibiotic exposures were suggestive of sicker patients

146
00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.820
getting antibiotics and doing worse, versus suggestive of a microbiome

147
00:09:06.840 --> 00:09:10.780
phenotype. And when we analyzed these various covariates, and you can see that

148
00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:13.320
in the paper, we did see that

149
00:09:14.300 --> 00:09:16.730
PIM exposure was an independent

150
00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:20.820
predictor of decreased overall survival, as was

151
00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:24.620
pre-lymphodepletion lactate dehydrogenase or LDH, as well as a

152
00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:26.440
worse performance status by ECOG.

153
00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:29.290
So in that multivariate analysis, this

154
00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:35.520
PIM exposure was associated and held up in terms of decreased

155
00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:38.860
progression-free and overall survival.

156
00:09:38.890 --> 00:09:42.240
And I'll also talk to you a little bit about other antibiotics that patients were

157
00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:46.240
exposed to that didn't decrease overall and progression-free survival, just to kind

158
00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:48.600
of round out that it's not just antibiotics

159
00:09:49.720 --> 00:09:53.500
given to the patients in the weeks prior to CAR T-cell therapy, but what the

160
00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:54.940
actual antibiotics target.

161
00:09:56.280 --> 00:10:00.269
So delving into that a little bit more, there was a subsequent paper

162
00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:04.160
from a multicenter cohort, investigators in Germany at three centers,

163
00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:07.500
Moffitt and MD Anderson Cancer Center, of which Dr.

